More than a year after implementing flexible remote work policies to help slow the spread of COVID-19, many workplaces are now asking their employees to return to the office.

But if the thought of giving up your WFH life fills you with dread, it may be time to look for a new job that allows you to work remotely 100% of the time.

To help your search, we put together a list of companies that regularly offer WFH positions. 

This list isn’t exhaustive; a lot of companies that previously only had in-office positions are moving toward more WFH jobs in order to attract qualified candidates and to save money on office rentals. So if you know of other companies that have gone fully remote, let us know in the comments below!

Then, check out the link in our bio for more info on the 32 companies included above.

“Dear Penny,

The last 10 years I was barely getting by financially. I had to ask my parents for money several times through the years. Now I have a great job making plenty of money. 

I wish I’d never told my parents because they constantly ask me for money. My friends know of my income. They are always expecting me to pay for things and help them. 

I told everybody because I was so proud of myself. But it was a stupid idea to tell people. Now I want to take it all back, every word of it. 

I know lying is wrong. But do you think it's OK for me to tell everybody something happened at work, everything fell apart, and now I'm barely making anything?”

Have you noticed lately that things seem to be getting more expensive? 

It’s not just you. 

The cost of things like rent, electricity and even food are rising, and we’re pretty much all starting to feel the pinch. 

In fact, the U.S. is experiencing the greatest spike in inflation since 2008. Consumer prices rose 5.4% in July compared to the year prior.

There is some good news though: Experts believe the jump in prices will only be temporary. (Keeping our fingers crossed!) 

In the meantime, if you’re looking to stabilize your rising costs, head to the link in our bio for a dozen savings tips to help you fight price inflation on everyday purchases.

More than a third of American households are inhabited by renters — which means more than a third of American households have landlords.

But the relationship between renter and landlord can be fraught, and it can be frustrating to be told to “deal with it” when you’re shelling out a third or your income (or more!) to live somewhere. 

The good news? As a renter, you have rights. Those rights may vary by state local jurisdiction, but the most basic right is to a residence that is in good enough condition to be lived in (also known as a warranty of habitability). 

Beyond that, responsibility for repairs and other issues that arise is dictated by what’s outlined in your lease agreement. That’s why it’s vital to read the entire lease and make sure you understand everything in it before you sign it. (And if you don’t understand something, ask!)

Head to the link in our bio for a ton of info on renters rights — and how to protect yourself. Plus, read up on your obligations as a renter (because yes, landlords have rights, too).

Splurging, it seems, is a lot of people’s dirty little secret.

In May, we surveyed nearly 2,000 Americans on their budgeting and spending habits and found 1 in 4 respondents have kept a purchase secret from their significant other out of fear of how they would react. 

But what is it that causes us to be so secretive about our spending?

“I think a lot of it has to do with just not talking about money,” said Brittany Davis, an Accredited Financial Counselor and associate financial planner at @brunchandbudget. “People don’t like to discuss money, and I think that needs to stop.”

So how do you open those lines of communication so you can begin managing your finances as a united front? 

Swipe for some tips to get you started. Then head to the link in our bio for more info — including how to know when to bring in professional help.
